The biggest lesson I learned from being wrong is that the status quo is rea=
lly powerful; Google is the default in every browser and on every phone, an=
d more importantly people have over two decades of habits of using Google f=
or everything. No matter how good alternatives may end up being, via chat i=
nterfaces or whatever else, it is a gargantuan lift to change that, and the=
 safe bet is that they won=E2=80=99t.

At the same time, that shows exactly why this moment is a tough one for Goo=
gle=E2=80=99s management. To what extent should they care about tail risk, =
and screw up their current business model to respond to something that may =
never end up being a thing? Go back to the last time Google was thought to =
be in trouble, when the rise of apps led to widespread predictions that ver=
tical search apps would peel away Google=E2=80=99s market share; Google sig=
nificantly overhauled Search to deliver vertical specific results for thing=
s like local, travel, etc., and introduced answers for common questions. Go=
ogle also got a lot faster =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s notable that =E2=80=9CI=
=E2=80=99m feeling lucky=E2=80=9D doesn=E2=80=99t actually exist in practic=
e because Google delivers search results now as you type. The end result wa=
s a company that continued to grow, even from its massive base (again, I ca=
n=E2=80=99t overstate just how wrong I was).

I suspect that Google will try to take a similar tack now: it helps that th=
e current iteration of chat interfaces are mostly useful for questions and =
topics that aren=E2=80=99t particularly monetizable anyways. Google could v=
ery well introduce chat-like responses, with the option to go deeper, for t=
he topics that make sense, while still delivering search results for everyt=
hing else, including the questions that actually monetize. And, frankly, it=
 will probably work. Distribution and habit really matter, and Google domin=
ates both.

And, I would add, this is also the right thing to do. The point of being ki=
nd to Kodak is to note that if something is truly disruptive a company is s=
crewed anyways. It=E2=80=99s not as if Kodak would still be a thriving enti=
ty had it dived head-first into digital cameras. It would have been competi=
ng on a fairly non-differentiated basis with brands like Sony and Nikon and=
 Canon, and then would have been swept away by the smartphone like everyone=
 else. Indeed, the fact that Kodak was strongest in the low-end space would=
 have meant that the company would have probably been screwed first. Someti=
mes things change, and that=E2=80=99s ok.

To bring this back to Google, and to try and restate the point I was drivin=
g at yesterday, Google will probably be fine, and if they=E2=80=99re not fi=
ne, well, I doubt there is much the company could do about it anyways, at l=
east as far as Search is concerned. What is smart is the continued diversif=
ication into other areas like YouTube (a massive beneficiary of AI), Google=
