OpenAI, Integration, and Microsoft
----------------------------------

I wanted to expound on a couple of points from the end of the Article (it r=
eally was quite long already). First this:

It is possible that OpenAI becomes the platform on which all other AI compa=
nies are built, which would ultimately mean the economic value of AI outsid=
e of OpenAI may be fairly modest; this is also the bull case for Google, as=
 they would be the most well-placed to be the Microsoft to OpenAI=E2=80=99s=
 AWS.

To go back to another part of Clayton Christensen=E2=80=99s theory, from Th=
e Innovator=E2=80=99s Solution ( https://claytonchristensen.com/books/the-i=
nnovators-solution/ ) :

When there is a performance gap =E2=80=94 when product functionality and re=
liability are not yet good enough to address the needs of customers in a gi=
ven tier of the market =E2=80=94 companies must compete by making the best =
possible products. In the race to do this, firms that build their products =
around proprietary, interdependent architectures enjoy an important competi=
tive advantage against competitors whose product architectures are modular,=
 because the standardization inherent in modularity takes too many degrees =
of design freedom away from engineers, and they cannot not optimize perform=
ance.

To the extent the theory holds you would expect that the most compelling ne=
w AI products would come from OpenAI, and indeed, that is what we saw with =
ChatGPT. At the same time, part of what made ChatGPT a big surprise is that=
 OpenAI has seemed much more focused on research and providing an API than =
in making products. Meanwhile, Microsoft is sitting at both ends: on one si=
de the company is basically paying for OpenAI=E2=80=99s costs via Azure cre=
dits; on the other it is Microsoft that made what is probably the most used=
 AI product in the market currently (GitHub CoPilot) and which is, accordin=
g to The Information=E2=80=99s recent ( https://www.theinformation.com/arti=
cles/microsoft-and-openai-working-on-chatgpt-powered-bing-in-challenge-to-g=
oogle ) | reporting ( https://www.theinformation.com/articles/ghost-writer-=
microsoft-looks-to-add-openais-chatbot-technology-to-word-email ) , moving =
aggressively to incorporate OpenAI into Bing and its productivity products.

That casts an interesting light on this rather weird report from Semafor ( =
https://www.semafor.com/article/01/09/2023/microsoft-eyes-10-billion-bet-on=
-chatgpt ) :

Microsoft has been in talks to invest $10 billion into the owner of ChatGPT=
, the wildly popular app that has thrilled casual users and artificial-inte=
lligence experts since its latest software was released last month, people =
familiar with the matter said. The funding, which would also include other =
venture firms, would value OpenAI, the firm behind ChatGPT, at $29 billion,=
 including the new investment, the people said. It=E2=80=99s unclear if the=
 deal has been finalized but documents sent to prospective investors in rec=
ent weeks outlining its terms indicated a targeted close by the end of 2022=
.

Microsoft=E2=80=99s infusion would be part of a complicated deal in which t=
he company would get 75% of OpenAI=E2=80=99s profits until it recoups its i=
nvestment, the people said. (It=E2=80=99s not clear whether money that Open=
AI spends on Microsoft=E2=80=99s cloud-computing arm would count toward eve=
ning its account.) After that threshold is reached, it would revert to a st=
ructure that reflects ownership of OpenAI, with Microsoft having a 49% stak=
e, other investors taking another 49% and OpenAI=E2=80=99s nonprofit parent=
 getting 2%. There=E2=80=99s also a profit cap that varies for each set of =
investors =E2=80=94 unusual for venture deals, which investors hope might r=
eturn 20 or 30 times their money. The terms and the investment amount could=
 change, and the deal could fall apart.

