ed to a =E2=80=9Ccapped-profit=E2=80=9D company when they realized they wou=
ld need a whole lot of money to build all of these models; assuming this re=
porting is accurate you can see traces of that transition in the profit cap=
 bit, and in the 2% for OpenAI=E2=80=99s nonprofit parent. What you can als=
o see traces of are the driver of this shift: the cost of computing. That=
=E2=80=99s where Microsoft comes in: first, the company has invested billio=
ns in Azure, and second, the company has products within which to leverage =
AI; this means that Microsoft can both offer more attractive rates and also=
 bet on itself to monetize the output.

Still, I didn=E2=80=99t expect to see Microsoft with 49% of the company; th=
at is a viable number given the dollar figures involved =E2=80=94 remember,=
 Microsoft already invested previously at a lower valuation =E2=80=94 but t=
his bit about being paid back preferentially is a bit odd. Then again, ever=
ything with OpenAI is odd, including the fact they are getting their comput=
e mostly for free via Azure credits. What it does suggest to me is that the=
re is a hidden downside from not simply building a normal company from the =
get-go: OpenAI somehow ended up in this spot where they are a client of Mic=
rosoft, and while that has seemed like a phenomenal deal to date, Microsoft=
=E2=80=99s pockets and patience are deeper and longer than just about anyon=
e.

